Communism is making a comeback in Russia.
Moscow — More than a year ago, while on sabbatical from my teaching position at a university in the United States, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination is not a stronghold of free speech.
But there is still some freedom preserved in this place.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once traveled across the country in an attempt to win the support of politicians not under the control of the Kremlin.
Protests erupted among the people.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate within the country.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party, on the other hand, is widely regarded as a product of historical legacy.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protest movement he initiated has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was dissolved on charges of "extremism," and its members are facing exile or investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media organizations, human rights advocates, or independent institutions are added to the "foreign agent" list — even worse — labeled as "undesirable."
Over the past year, Russia has been plunged into a state of non-freedom, which, though not distant, has been very intense.
For example, a law designating foreign agents was enacted in 2012, aimed at undermining or discrediting entities or individuals engaged in "political activities" while simultaneously receiving funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where forwarding tweets now also serves as a justification for labeling someone as a foreign agent.
The label of "unwanted person" will result in your complete eradication.
So far this year alone, the list of foreign agents has added a record 101 entities.
The total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be listed on the list because they "influence the country's politics."
But the core goal of news and propaganda work is certainly to influence politics.
And this is precisely the problem: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics for the foreseeable future, he perceives criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite enduring all this silence and persecution, it was an unlikely group—the Communist Party—that survived and became the sole genuine opposition within the Kremlin.
This has largely been due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — that is, urging people to support the forces most likely to defeat the candidates backed by the Kremlin — as the Communist Party showed strong performance in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that the Communist Party candidate won 18.9% of the votes in the State Duma (parliament), while the United Russia party, supported by the Kremlin, received nearly 49.8%.
But the Communists refused to acknowledge this outcome, insisting that the voting results had been manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while the United Russia party should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, communists seem to be more respected than Putin now.
But they are no longer the original Communist Party members.
Not only do they not deny the pleasures of the material world, but party members even wear fur coats, are enthusiastic about traveling abroad, driving foreign cars, and using social media.
Some people are millionaires—for example, Pavel Grudinin, the charming agricultural minister, who was banned from participating in last month's election.
Although the party is still led by Gennadiy Zyuganov, who is 77 years old, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger party members.
Take Nikolai Bondarenko, for example.
36-year-old Bondarenko, nicknamed "Red Navalny," severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister claimed that Russians should be able to "eat better" with a monthly salary of just 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko recorded on his YouTube channel his efforts to prove the minister wrong.
Despite being threatened with disqualification from running, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the parliamentary elections held last month.
Although he received support from the smart voting system of Navalny, he still lost to the candidate of the United Russia party.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently drafted a title for a protest activity accusing "the state and government have taken over United Russia."
Then there's Anastasia Yudashova, who is 43 years old.
Like Bondarenko, she astonishingly lost the last election.
But she remains very — — and increasingly — — popular.
Thanks to the Smart Voting system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Ngarileva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the modernization efforts of the Communist Party reflect people's nostalgia for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although the country that achieved these ideals was strict, it was still not devoid of fairness and compassion.
Moreover, like Navalny the liberal, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which one person's eccentricity does not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that the Kremlin's opponents are increasingly uniting: forming a "united Russia" that can oppose Putin.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as Czech Donald Trump — failed to be re-elected as prime minister, as the opposition alliance put aside their ideological differences and formed a united front. Its leader, Petr Fiala, is likely to lead the new government together with another opposition coalition.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also present a unified electoral list in next year's parliamentary elections and field a single candidate for the position of prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, so Babic is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Overthrowing Putin would be far more difficult, and it's not hard to foresee more measures aimed at dismantling the Communist Party.
But the above approach also poses risks for the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims that Russian democracy "has not died out," citing the existence of an "active opposition" as evidence, which suggests that he at least still has an interest in pretending that Russia is not being led toward near-authoritarianism.
Putin said he only wants stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia into more turbulent situations.
If the Kremlin were to create and enforce rules capriciously, as it has with the Russian liberals, driving the Communist Party underground, social explosion would be more likely to occur.
But if it decides to stop suppressing them, Russian communists—yes, communists—could become an influential force that cannot be ignored.
